title: 2009 Afghanistan Presidential Election Fraud Assessment: Category C1 - Polling Stations in Which 600 or More Valid Votes Were Cast AND in Which One Candidate Received 95% or More of the Total Votes Cast
name: 2009 Afghanistan Presidential Election Fraud Assessment: Category C1 - Polling Stations in Which 600 or More Valid Votes Were Cast AND in Which One Candidate Received 95% or More of the Total Votes Cast
description:
The Afghanistan presidential election results have been marred by accusations of widespread fraud. After receiving thousands of complaints, the Independent Election Complaints Commission (ECC) conducted its own audit and recount to determine the degree of voting irregularities.

For this they divided the 30,000 plus polling stations spread across 34 Afghanistan provinces into two main groups. One consisting of polling stations that were free of fraud and the other set was further divided into six different categories as outlined by ECC in the Oct 10, 2009 document titled "ECC Policy on Audit and Recount Evaluations". The data in this shapefile is based on Audit/Recount evaluation category

A1: Polling stations in which 600 or more valid votes were cast

A2: Polling stations in which 600 or more total votes were cast, except those already covered in A1

B1: Polling stations with more than 100 votes in which one candidate received 95 percent or more of the total votes cast

B2: Polling stations in which one candidate received 95 percent or more of the total valid votes cast, except those already covered in B1

C1: Polling stations in which 600 or more valid votes were cast AND in which one candidate received 95% or more of the total votes cast

C2: Polling stations in which 600 or more total votes were cast AND in which one candidate received 95% or more of the valid votes

The shapefile was generated by aggregating vote counts at all polling stations meeting category (A1 A2, B1, B2, C1, C2), into Polling centers, which were then further aggregated at the province level for the major candidates. These polling stations formed a universe for a sample which was then used to determine the coefficient of vote reduction. Although we do not have coefficient of reduction for each of these categories, the shapefile shows the number of polling stations and vote counts by candidate and by province that were eligible for reduction.

Caveat: The vote count estimates are likely to be a bit higher than actual due to process of aggregating data from polling station to polling centers and then onto province.
